    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-03-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-03-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="476"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d476">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 811.7111/64.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 81.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-03-17">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 17, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to my Note No. 75 of the 12th
                    instant relative to “Chief Sam’s” plan for promoting negro emigration to the
                    Gold Coast Colony I have the honour to inform you, under instructions from Sir
                    Edward Grey, that the ordinance in question is being passed.</p>
                <p>In this connection I may add that the British Vice Consul at Portland, Maine, has
                    been instructed not to issue British papers to the steamer <hi rend="italic"
                        >Curityba</hi> which I understand has been purchased by “Chief Sam” and is
                    the property of the Akim Trading Company, of South Dakota.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cecil Spring Rice</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
